<subSubSection id="3F9B891EE97342E69417757BE80FDF75" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="73" pageId="27" pageNumber="72" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="6822FA016A73F2E75558677189883D53" pageId="27" pageNumber="72">General distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F3A4A0D10A0EF0702CABDE122013E2FB" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="73" pageId="27" pageNumber="72">
. The distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="602AD8BC9B00F482438275D6628FB643" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. sesuvioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="27" pageNumber="72" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="sesuvioides">
<emphasis id="DE693B8070B300EFBDD0FEDE6468810C" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="72">S. sesuvioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was mapped in 
<bibRefCitation id="3367691B36099E5B337242960EA1C0C1" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" author="Sukhorukov, AP" journalOrPublisher="Botany Letters" pageId="36" pageNumber="81" pagination="135 - 153" refId="B76" refString="Sukhorukov, AP, Verloove, F, Alonso, MA, Belyaeva, IV, Chapano, C, Crespo, MB, El Aouni, MH, El Mokni, R, Maroyi, A, Shekede, MD, Vicente, A, Dreyer, A, Kushunina, M, 2017. Chorological and taxonomic notes on African plants, 2. Botany Letters 164 (2): 135 - 153, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" title="Chorological and taxonomic notes on African plants, 2." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" volume="164" year="2017">Sukhorukov et al. (2017)</bibRefCitation>
, but the presence of this species was erroneously indicated in the 
<pageBreakToken id="2D624706B3B87F8863DCD7F96B91D1A7" pageId="28" pageNumber="73" start="start">eastern</pageBreakToken>
part of South Africa, due to a misapplication of the name 
<normalizedToken id="9C272EA9E46E09B53BC4D408FF0B85EF" originalValue="“Kleinfontein”">&quot;Kleinfontein&quot;</normalizedToken>
. The record from Kleinfontein (24 Oct 1922, 
<emphasis id="BCEC7867C48B58F1C3DB35AA01424A97" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="73">Dinter 4151</emphasis>
, BM!) indeed belongs to the small village located south of 
<normalizedToken id="90CC1CCE3A9F16B372B64D32B233AB00" originalValue="Maltahöhe">Maltahoehe</normalizedToken>
(Hardap Region, Namibia) and not to the village in Gauteng province (South Africa) mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation id="0BC2D06162C111A22E683AFE3329859C" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" author="Sukhorukov, AP" journalOrPublisher="Botany Letters" pageId="36" pageNumber="81" pagination="135 - 153" refId="B76" refString="Sukhorukov, AP, Verloove, F, Alonso, MA, Belyaeva, IV, Chapano, C, Crespo, MB, El Aouni, MH, El Mokni, R, Maroyi, A, Shekede, MD, Vicente, A, Dreyer, A, Kushunina, M, 2017. Chorological and taxonomic notes on African plants, 2. Botany Letters 164 (2): 135 - 153, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" title="Chorological and taxonomic notes on African plants, 2." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" volume="164" year="2017">Sukhorukov et al. (2017)</bibRefCitation>
. The authors came to this conclusion after tracing the journeys of Kurt Moritz Dinter, who only visited Namibia (it was known at the time as &quot;South-West Africa&quot;: 
<bibRefCitation id="5CD1A26D42F78A4D73EDF477FF5F5A05" author="Glen, HF" journalOrPublisher="1. The Royal Botanic Gardens Kew, London" pageId="33" pageNumber="78" refId="B26" refString="Glen, HF, Germishuizen, G, 2010. Botanical exploration of southern Africa, 2nd ed. [Strelitzia 26] South African National Biodiversity Institute, Pretoria." title="Botanical exploration of southern Africa, 2 nd ed. [Strelitzia 26] South African National Biodiversity Institute, Pretoria." year="2010">Glen and Germishuizen 2010</bibRefCitation>
). Likewise, the lectotype specimen was not collected at Garpia river near Swellendam, Western Cape (as indicated in 
<bibRefCitation id="74148E878764636B45B479FD79B6A3D7" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" author="Sukhorukov, AP" journalOrPublisher="Botany Letters" pageId="36" pageNumber="81" pagination="135 - 153" refId="B76" refString="Sukhorukov, AP, Verloove, F, Alonso, MA, Belyaeva, IV, Chapano, C, Crespo, MB, El Aouni, MH, El Mokni, R, Maroyi, A, Shekede, MD, Vicente, A, Dreyer, A, Kushunina, M, 2017. Chorological and taxonomic notes on African plants, 2. Botany Letters 164 (2): 135 - 153, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" title="Chorological and taxonomic notes on African plants, 2." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" volume="164" year="2017">Sukhorukov et al. (2017)</bibRefCitation>
), but on the banks of the Orange River (or Gariep River, spelled by 
<normalizedToken id="28A3C07B4F4D49FB121EC8AB786564D3" originalValue="Drège">Drege</normalizedToken>
as 
<normalizedToken id="A435CDD36DC24C328078ADD2B9E44652" originalValue="“Garip”">&quot;Garip&quot;</normalizedToken>
), where 
<taxonomicName id="19E22AFCF9449476D961B7178D44A3F6" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. sesuvioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="28" pageNumber="73" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="sesuvioides">
<emphasis id="D519D7E84D1A70A5BAD1109B32823A4E" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="73">S. sesuvioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is frequently found. Therefore the records of 
<taxonomicName id="EFBAAF393EEAF1C6A5C1FAC5D790F0FB" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. sesuvioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="28" pageNumber="73" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="sesuvioides">
<emphasis id="EB99186442A8F5992FDB86676EAF323D" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="73">S. sesuvioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Gauteng and the Western Cape provinces (
<bibRefCitation id="30FA978892F68124AAF1E88D6031EA77" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" author="Sukhorukov, AP" journalOrPublisher="Botany Letters" pageId="36" pageNumber="81" pagination="135 - 153" refId="B76" refString="Sukhorukov, AP, Verloove, F, Alonso, MA, Belyaeva, IV, Chapano, C, Crespo, MB, El Aouni, MH, El Mokni, R, Maroyi, A, Shekede, MD, Vicente, A, Dreyer, A, Kushunina, M, 2017. Chorological and taxonomic notes on African plants, 2. Botany Letters 164 (2): 135 - 153, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" title="Chorological and taxonomic notes on African plants, 2." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" volume="164" year="2017">Sukhorukov et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
) are erroneous. In South Africa, the distribution pattern of 
<taxonomicName id="15B81C9A54041036447698747E50A8A7" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. sesuvioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="28" pageNumber="73" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="sesuvioides">
<emphasis id="20B8010FCF5F360EF8C0E0AA51FC8557" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="73">S. sesuvioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted to the Richtersveld and the lower Orange River valley (Northern Cape province). Records in Namibia and Angola are from the Namib desert (
<bibRefCitation id="EA295F9A2B8A20B609A654967FFC07C2" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" author="Sukhorukov, AP" journalOrPublisher="Botany Letters" pageId="36" pageNumber="81" pagination="135 - 153" refId="B76" refString="Sukhorukov, AP, Verloove, F, Alonso, MA, Belyaeva, IV, Chapano, C, Crespo, MB, El Aouni, MH, El Mokni, R, Maroyi, A, Shekede, MD, Vicente, A, Dreyer, A, Kushunina, M, 2017. Chorological and taxonomic notes on African plants, 2. Botany Letters 164 (2): 135 - 153, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" title="Chorological and taxonomic notes on African plants, 2." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/23818107.2017.1311281" volume="164" year="2017">Sukhorukov et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
, see also Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4CDAC6783FF953AF2F5A5B5F288D8E04" captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figure 19. Distribution map of Sesuvium sesuvioides." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.92.22205.figure19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/179522" pageId="28" pageNumber="73">19</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="BB3F38717DF7BE5D45F9E2E4CF5B853A" ID-Zenodo-Dep="1166638" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.92.22205.figure19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/179522" pageId="28" pageNumber="73" start="Figure 19" startId="F19">
<paragraph id="B6620D30D270329CD757991A15F742CA" pageId="28" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis id="882B3C2804CF7B2C53DB113CA5ED1BB4" bold="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="73">Figure 19.</emphasis>
Distribution map of 
<taxonomicName id="9552640D195947008126DAA3CB5B834B" authorityName="Verdc., Kew Bull. 12 (2): 349" authorityYear="1957" baseAuthorityName="Fenzl" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Aizoaceae" genus="Sesuvium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Sesuvium sesuvioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="28" pageNumber="73" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="sesuvioides">
<emphasis id="11023B285596FEA3323AE15BB60CF4A7" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="73">Sesuvium sesuvioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="6DBFE25C9A1421F070E7FB807A623101" pageId="28" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName id="ABB1CFD49DC0CBE35770945FA83DF769" authorityName="Verdc., Kew Bull. 12 (2): 349" authorityYear="1957" baseAuthorityName="Fenzl" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Aizoaceae" genus="Sesuvium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Sesuvium sesuvioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="28" pageNumber="73" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="sesuvioides">
<emphasis id="8ED17A640D223CD5483E408D5DB75DBA" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="73">Sesuvium sesuvioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a large geographical distribution with an estimated EOO of 501,893 km2, but its AOO is only 60 km2 (which would place it in EN). Many localities, especially in Namibia, are in desert areas and are presumably under little threat. Some populations collected in the past are likely to be in protected areas today. However, the current size of the populations is unknown. Therefore, the species should be considered as Data Deficient (DD) according to the IUCN Red List Criteria (
<bibRefCitation id="0F39A41C53B884790DFB0DCA1B459FB1" author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="2. INEAC Publ., Brussels" pageId="34" pageNumber="79" publicationUrl="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" refId="B41" refString="IUCN, 2017. Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria, Version 13., http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf [ [accessed 7 Nov 2017] ]" title="Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria, Version 13" url="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" year="2017">IUCN 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
